{"id":"2109.03518","submitter":"J. Pascal Gollin","authors":"J. Pascal Gollin, Karl Heuer, Konstantinos Stavropoulos","title":"Disjoint dijoins for classes of dicuts in finite and infinite digraphs","comments":"24 pages, 1 figure","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A dicut in a directed graph is a cut for which all of its edges are directed\nto a common side of the cut. A famous theorem of Lucchesi and Younger states\nthat in every finite digraph the least size of a set of edges meeting every\nnon-empty dicut equals the maximum number of disjoint dicuts in that digraph.\nSuch sets are called dijoins. Woodall conjectured a dual statement. He asked\nwhether the maximum number of disjoint dijoins in a directed graph equals the\nminimum size of a non-empty dicut.\n  We study a modification of this question where we restrict our attention to\ncertain classes of non-empty dicuts, i.e. whether for a class $\\mathfrak{B}$ of\ndicuts of a directed graph the maximum number of disjoint sets of edges meeting\nevery dicut in $\\mathfrak{B}$ equals the size of a minimum dicut in\n$\\mathfrak{B}$. In particular, we verify this questions for nested classes of\nfinite dicuts, for the class of dicuts of minimum size, and for classes of\ninfinite dibonds, and we investigate how this generalised setting relates to a\ncapacitated version of this question.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 8 Sep 2021 09:37:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-09-09"}
